facts.value:
Joseph Morse came to America with his father and mother in the ship "Increase", which sailed from England in April 1635.  He was 20 years of age.  He came to Watertown, Massachusetts.  He took the oath of freeman in 1635 and was a member of the first church at Watertown.  
     Joseph Morse went from Watertown, Massachusetts to Dedham, Mass. in 1637, where he was number 29 among the signers of the Dedham Compact.  He received the maximum alottment of 12 acres of land.  
    He married Hannah Phillips in 1638, probably at Watertown.  It is not known whether Hannah Phillips was sister or cousin or how she was related, if at all, to Henry Phillips and the pastor George Phillips of Watertown.  she was  most likely sister of Henry Phillips.  
     Joseph was among the first subscribers to found the town of Medfield.  But while he was building a house at Medfield, Mass., his family were at Dorchester, Mass.  He died before the family went to Medfield.

Time Line for John Lawrence (1667 - 1747) the 2nd son of Nathanel and Sarah Morse Lawrence
1667, 29 Jul - Groton, Mass - John Lawrence born at paternal homestead near Gibbet Hill
Groton Mass Early Birth Records
LAURANCE (see also Lawrence) 
John, s. Nathaniel and Sarah, July 29, 1667. CTR 
1687, 9 Nov - Groton, Mass - John married Anna Tarbel Nov 9, 1687 in Groton and had 10 children. Anna was the daughter of Thomas and Hannah Longley Lawrence - Ceremony performed by the Rev. Gershom Hobart
1687 to 1693 - Groton, Mass - He was a farmer and a blacksmith in Groton until 1693 when he moved to Lexington Cambridge Farms to a residence on Bedford Road.
1692, 16 Mar - Groton, Mass - John Lawrence found listed in a 11 man garrison of William Greens established for the protection of the town. William Greene and associates dwelt with district No. 1 from the first parish meeting-house southerly and easterly
1693 - Cambridge Farms, Lexington, Mass - Purchased home on Bedford Road in Lexington known as "Old Lawrence Place" This was situated on the north-western border of the princint, on the edge of Tophet Swamp. The locality was at that time called "the world's end."
1699, 9 Feb - Cambridge Farms, Lexington, Mass - John and Anna were received in the church of Lexington
1702 - Cambridge Farms, Lexington, Mass - He was parish assessor
1705 - Cambridge Farms, Lexington, Mass - He was constable
1716, 17, 22, 25, 26, 31 - Cambridge Farms, Lexington, Mass -Served as selectman
1719 - Cambridge Farms, Lexington, Mass - tythingman
1724, 14 Apr - Cambridge Farms, Lexington, Mass - Father Nathanel died while living with John at the 'Worlds End" home on Bedford Road.
1747, 12 Mar - Cambridge Farms, Lexington, Mass - John Lawrence died - John, Mar. 12, 1747. - NEHGS Lexington record of Deaths - Lexington, Middlesex, Mass Death Records: Lawrence, John, Mar. 12, 1747
1747, Mar - Burial C. 84 Old Burying Ground, Lexington, Middlesex, Massachusetts, USA - Gravestone found in Lexington.
